12. Phase I Project Summary¶

1. Introduction to the Case Study Go Back to Glossary¶

The loan providing companies find it hard to give loans to the people due to their insufficient or non-existent credit history. Because of that, some consumers use it as their advantage by becoming a defaulter. As an data analyst for a consumer finance company, which specializes in lending various types of loans to urban customers, I have been tasked to use EDA to analyze the patterns present in the data. This will ensure that the applicants who can repay the loan are not rejected.

When the company receives a loan application, the company must decide for loan approval based on the applicants profile. Two types of risks are associated with the banks decision:

If the applicant is likely to repay the loan, then not approving the loan results in a loss of business to the company

If the applicant is not likely to repay the loan, i.e. he/she is likely to default, then approving the loan may lead to a financial loss for the company.

</span>

The data given below contains the information about the loan application at the time of applying for the loan. It contains two types of scenarios:

The client with payment difficulties: he/she had late payment more than X days on at least one of the first Y instalments of the loan in our sample

All other cases: All other cases when the payment is paid on time.

When a client applies for a loan, there are four types of decisions that could be taken by the client/company):

Approved: The Company has approved loan Application

Cancelled: The client cancelled the application sometime during approval. Either the client changed her/his mind about the loan or in some cases due to a higher risk of the client he received worse pricing which he did not want.

Refused: The company had rejected the loan (because the client does not meet their requirements etc.).

Unused offer: Loan has been cancelled by the client but on different stages of the process.

In this case study, we will use EDA to understand how consumer attributes and loan attributes influence the tendency of default.

2. Provided information and Data Files Go Back to Glossary¶

This Analysis has has 3 files that holds following information:

'application_data.csv contains all the information of the client at the time of application. This file holds the information regarding customers with or without payment difficulties.

'previous_application.csv' contains information about the clients previous loan data. It contains the data whether the previous application had been Approved, Cancelled, Refused or Unused.

'columns_description.csv' is data dictionary which contains description for each of the variables stored in above two files, this file is particularly helpful to understand the contents in each of the above two files.

3. Project Goal Go Back to Glossary¶

We will try to achieve following for this case study

Problem Statement: Identify the set of attributes that have higher probability of payment defaults. This information can then be used to train our model to semi-automate the loan process for approvals, deciding credit amount etc.

The goal is sub divided into

Data Preparation manipulating the Application Data and Previous Application data into a form that can readily and accurately be analyzed to achieve the above given problem statement.

Exploratory Data Analysis use a set of univariates,multivariate, parametric and non-parametric analysis to identify factors that has higher probability of payment defaults.

5. Custom Functions Go Back to Glossary¶

In order to speed up our tasks, as well as to achieve the goal in a LEAN way, we will create some Custom Functions. All our custome functions will be listed in this section along with a short description of what is expected out of these functions.

  1. yCube_DescribePlus - This function takes a Panda Data Frame as an input and returns another data frame that contains the Descriptive Statistics along with some additional details like Total number of rows and columns, Data Type of each column, Size of each Column, Null Count and Percentage in each column.

  2. yCube_iConsistent- This function takes two argument, a data frame and a list and returns the name of the column and occurance percentage of the list items in the dataframe. This function will be used to identify Null, inconsistent as well as 0 values in our data set.

  3. yCube_Prop_Replace - This function takes 3 mandatory argument and 1 optional argument, and is used to replace the null value in a column with the sampe proportion of existing content in that same column. The optional arugment can be used to use group by method if you want to replace null value with proportion based on value in another column.

  4. yCube_iQr_gRp - This function will take 5 arguments and returns new columns with a suffix _out. We will use this function to calculate Inter Quartile Range of a column based on Rational Subgrouping

  5. yCube_iQr - This function will work much like the previous iQr function but without Rational Subgrouping and takes 3 argument, data frame, column name and threshold for IQR.

  6. yCube_Cramer_V - This is a modified version of Cramer V function custom function, which is used to calculate Correlation Coefficient with Nominal Target variable

  7. yCube_sqRtransform - This function helps us to identify outliers in count data, it takes 4 argument (3 required and one optional) and returns a new column with a suffix _out which holds Normal or Outlier values. The outlier identifcation can be changed by modifying the 3rd agrument in the formula, which by default is kept at 2. To know more about Identifying outliers in count data please refer to this section

def yCube_DescribePlus(DataFrame):
    df_des = DataFrame.describe(include='all')
    df_des.loc['Data Type'] = DataFrame.dtypes
    df_des.loc['Size'] = len(DataFrame)
    df_des.loc['Null Count'] = DataFrame.isnull().sum()
    df_des.loc['Null Percent'] = DataFrame.isnull().sum()*100/len(DataFrame)
    print('Your Data Frame has following number of Rows and Columns: ' + str(DataFrame.shape))
    return df_des

def yCube_iConsistent(DataFrame,iConsistentList):
    i_Val = DataFrame.isin(iConsistentList).sum()
    i_Val_p = 100*(i_Val)/len(DataFrame)
    i_Val_t =  pd.concat([i_Val, i_Val_p], axis=1)
    i_Val_t = i_Val_t.rename(
    columns = {0 : 'Inconsistent Values', 1 : '%'})
    i_Val_t = i_Val_t[
        i_Val_t.iloc[:,1] != 0].sort_values(
    '%', ascending=False).round(1)
    print ('Your selected dataframe has ' + str(DataFrame.shape[1]) + 'columns.\n'      
        'There are ' + str(i_Val_t.shape[0]) +
            ' columns that have inconsistent values.')
    return i_Val_t

def yCube_Prop_Replace(dFrame, ColR, ColF,ColFVal):
    IsNull = dFrame[ColR].isnull()
    FilVal = dFrame[dFrame[ColF].isin([ColFVal])& dFrame[ColR].notnull()]
    FilVal = FilVal[ColR]
    iMpSam = set(FilVal)
    
    PropFrame = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Name','Count','Proportion'])
    for y in iMpSam:
        PropFrame.loc[-1] = [y,dFrame.loc[dFrame[ColR]==y].shape[0],0]
        PropFrame.index = PropFrame.index+1
    PropFrame['Proportion']=PropFrame['Count']/PropFrame['Count'].sum()
    ToReplace = np.random.choice(PropFrame['Name'],size=(dFrame[ColR].isnull().sum(),), p = PropFrame['Proportion'])
    dFrame.loc[IsNull,ColR]=ToReplace    
    return dFrame

def yCube_iQr_gRp(df, Cln, gCln,c, nCln=None):
    if nCln is None:
        nCln = Cln+'_out'
    iqr = df.groupby([gCln])[Cln].quantile(0.75)-df.groupby([gCln])[Cln].quantile(0.25)
    l = df.groupby([gCln])[Cln].quantile(0.25) - (c-.3)*iqr
    u = df.groupby([gCln])[Cln].quantile(0.75) + (c-.3)*iqr
    
    df_ = pd.merge(df,l,on =gCln,how ='inner',suffixes=('', '_lq'))
    df = pd.merge(df_,u,on =gCln,how ='inner',suffixes=('', '_uq'))
    
    df[nCln] = np.where((df[Cln] <=df[Cln+'_lq']), 
                                 'Outlier', np.where((df[Cln]>= df[Cln+'_uq']), 
                                                        'Outlier', 'Normal'))
    df.drop(Cln+'_lq', axis=1, inplace=True)
    df.drop(Cln+'_uq', axis=1, inplace=True)
    return df

def yCube_iQr(dataFrame, CurrentCln, c,NewCln=None):
    if NewCln is None:
        NewCln = CurrentCln+'_out'
    Q1=dataFrame[CurrentCln].quantile(0.25)
    Q3=dataFrame[CurrentCln].quantile(0.75)
    IQR=Q3-Q1
    L_Outlier = (Q1-((c-.3)*IQR))
    U_Outlier = (Q3+((c-.3)*IQR))
    
    cond_quartile= [
    (dataFrame[CurrentCln].isnull()),
    (dataFrame[CurrentCln] <= L_Outlier),
    (dataFrame[CurrentCln] > L_Outlier) & (dataFrame[CurrentCln] < U_Outlier),
    (dataFrame[CurrentCln]>= U_Outlier)
    ]

    values = [np.nan,'Outlier', 'Normal', 'Outlier']


    dataFrame[NewCln] = np.select(cond_quartile, values)
    return dataFrame

def YCube_Cramer_V(x,y):
    result=-1
    if len(x.value_counts())==1 :
        print("First variable is constant")
    elif len(y.value_counts())==1:
        print("Second variable is constant")
    else:   
        conf_matrix=pd.crosstab(x, y)
        if conf_matrix.shape[0]==2:
            correct=False
        else:
            correct=True
        chi2 = stats.chi2_contingency(conf_matrix, correction=correct)[0]
        n = sum(conf_matrix.sum())
        phi2 = chi2/n
        r,k = conf_matrix.shape
        phi2corr = max(0, phi2 - ((k-1)*(r-1))/(n-1))    
        rcorr = r - ((r-1)**2)/(n-1)
        kcorr = k - ((k-1)**2)/(n-1)
        result=np.sqrt(phi2corr / min( (kcorr-1), (rcorr-1)))
    return round(result,6)

6D. Visually inspect Application Data Frame Go Back to Glossary¶

Its very important in any data analysis to spend a good amount of time in understanding the data file visually. Reading through columns and rows, and assessing the information in them. We will not be able to understand everything just with visual analysis, but the idea is understanding each column in detail, what information they hold and how we can assess these columns keeping the end goal in mind.

Remember, Data Analytics is as much of an Art than Science, so lets first be good artists before becoming scientists.

Some of the immediate understanding after visually inspecting the application data file and description file are

  • there are null values in most of the columns

  • there are XNA and blank values (empty string) also in the data set

  • we have date and time column given in numeric format instead of time format, for example applicants DOB is given in number of days instead of Years and Months

  • date value columns contain -ve values

  • there are around 20 columns containing document submission details, but most of the rows in these columns are empty

  • income type, occupation type and organization type columns contain very vital information, but these columns have unstructured data (different nomenclatures for same type of information)

  • there are set of columns which doesnt provide any critical input for our analysis for example flag employee phone, flat email address etc.

5E. Descriptive statistics of Application Data Frame Go Back to Glossary¶

We will use a custom function to get a full descriptive statistic of our columns. These details will help us validate some of the observations that we had in our Visual Inspection section above, like

  • -ve values in date columns DAYS_BIRTH, DAYS_EMPLOYED, DAYS_REGISTRATION, DAYS_ID_PUBLISH

  • a view on spread (measure of dispersion) of numerical data value columns in terms of Minimum, Maximum, Standard Deviation some of the columns like AMT_INCOME_TOTAL, AMT_CREDIT, AMT_ANNUITY have high spread so we can expect these columns to have a lot of outliers

  • a view of measure of central tendency using measure like Mean and Median (50th percentile)

  • count of unique values in each of our numeric columns

  • count of null values in each column, some of the columns contain as high as 60% of null values

  • a view on type of column we are dealing with (int, obj, float etc.), this will help us to run relevant exploratory data analysis and statistical functions later in our analysis

6F. Identify, impute or delete Unstructured Categorical value columns Go Back to Glossary¶

Not all data is created equal or the same, even in most of structured organizations like financial institutions, we may come across datapoints which are very unstructured. These types of categorical values are rather very annoying while performing data analytics, and often leads to incorrect or inconclusive results.

For example, a Marital status data should have following categorical values Married, Widowed, Separated, Divorced and Single. Now thanks to synonyms in English language few will call Single as Unmarried and enter a separate data in the database. These will not create any problem for humans as we can interpret it easily, but for a Machine to process, these two have separate values hence separate meanings.

In this section of our data cleaning we will look into similar situations in our dataset and correct them as we identify them.

6F. i. Name Income Type, Occupation Type and Organization Type Go Back to Glossary¶

NAME_INCOME_TYPE, OCCUPATION_TYPE and ORGANIZATION_TYPE we will spend considerable amount of time in these columns as they hold key information needed for our analysis.

Here is what we gonna do

There are around 97k null values in OCCUPATION_TYPE, we will use the proportion replacement custom function called yCube_Prop_Replace to replace the missing values in this column with same proportion of existing values, one thing to keep in mind is that the content of this column is dependent on NAME_INCOME_TYPE column, so our proportion replace will have to take care of that. Luckily in our custom function we cann pass a content variable to replace values for specific Name Income Group.

6F. ii. Name Type Suite Go Back to Glossary¶

NAME_TYPE_SUITE - Now lets look at another column that contains some un-structured information. This column contains information on who accompanied applicant during the application process. This column contains highly fragmented details and contain 5% of the null value.

We will create a new column NAME_TYPE_SUITE_NEW which can represent the same information but as

Accompanied if the applicant was accompanied by anyone during the application processor

Unaccompanied if the applicant did not have any company during the application process.

6G. Identify, impute or delete Empty and Null value columns Go Back to Glossary¶

In general null or empty values are not illegal, specially during multiple data source mapping processes we will get some empty values, but what is important is to have a legitimate explanation for the null value, as well as clear view of which all columns contain null values. We also need to identify mandatory columns (those which cannot have null values)

Some of the statistical functions doen't like to have null values at all, as it will skew the analysis, knowing the presence of null values in each column will help us to take decissions while selecting statistical tools.

In this section we will analyze all of our columns for the Null values. We will use our yCube_iConsistent function to identify Null values by giving np.nan as a list input. Any column that contains more than 30% of the null value possesses big risk in our data analysis, as it will skew our inferences and may also result in incorrect outcomes. We will list column names containing the blank values, we will analyze then and take a decision if we want to keep them for our analysis or anote them to exclude during certain analysis.

EXT_SOURCE1:3 These columns hold the external credit score of the client and contains few null entries. Rather than keeping three variables in our study, we will take average of these three columns and keep on column called EXT_SOURCE_AVG

CNT_SOCIAL_CIRCLE We have four columns of critical information regarding Clients Social Circle. These information are very hard to come by specially in todays world governed by data privacy. This columns will help us predict client behaviour based on the social circle, which is very interesting, however the problem with these columns is that they contain a way more Zero values and few null values, that we anticipated. As a work around we will convert these Count values to a categorical column CNT_SOCIAL_CIRCLE_DEF with a condition.

AMT_REQ_CREDIT_BUREAU There are set of columns that holds information regarding query to credit bureau regarding the applicant, that was done as close to as hour before the application tracing it back up to last one year. There is no need to keep a multiple dependent column, instead we will take the mode of all these columns and create a new column called AMT_REQ_CREDIT_BUREAU

Rest of the columns will be deleted later during the final sanitization phase with [proper explanation](#appdata_unwanteddata).

Here are the set of columns will Null Value, the count of inconsistent value (null in this case) and relevant percentage is given here for your reference.

6H. i. Negative Values in Date Columns Go Back to Glossary¶

DAYS_BIRTH, DAYS_EMPLOYED, DAYS_REGISTRATION, DAYS_ID_PUBLISH All of these columns contain the information regarding total number of days, for eg. DAY_BIRTH contains the Total Number of days from the applicants birth until the application date. Also as noted earlier in the visual section, some of these values are negative.

Most of the date values express in integers should contain only positive values, but there are few situations where the same is express in -ve. For example days past due many a time is expressed in -ve terms as it gives us the direction along with the magnitude. However in our case, all of the day columns can be expressed in +ve integer. We will use python abs() fucntion to perform this action

Here is the new and changed Data Value Columns with all positive values

7G. i. Negative Values in Date Columns Go Back to Glossary¶

Negative Value days columns - In this segment we will put focus on some of the columns that holds date, days and time values. While some days values stored in integer format (as count of days) can be represented in negative format to indicate the direction (eg. Past Due is generally noted in -ve format to indicate how many days has already passed by froma specific due date), but in our data set, our date value columns (critical ones needed for analysis) can very well only be represented as positive integers.

DAYS_DECISION, DAYS_FIRST_DUE, DAYS_LAST_DUE_1ST_VERSION, DAYS_LAST_DUE, DAYS_TERMINATION All of these columns contain the information regarding total number of days for certain category of information, and can verywell be only represented in positive format.

Rest of columns are of no importance for our analysis except `DAYS_DECISION`. We will use python `abs()` function to covert this into positive value.

In [45]:
df_pre['DAYS_DECISION'] = df_pre['DAYS_DECISION'].abs()

7G. ii. Finding columns with XNA,NA,XAP Values Go Back to Glossary¶

We will now check our data frame for any inconsistent values like XNA, XAP, N/A etc. We will reuse our old function yCube_iConsistent for this job. As you can see we have quite a bit of inconsistent values in our columns, while most of these we can treat with various logic, but unfortunately some of them are either quite impossible to work with, or we may want to remove them as an existing column will suffice. Any column that we will delete will be discussed in our section here, but just to build the right prespective, we will have to delete following columns as they have too many inconsistent values without any logic for us to replace them NAME_PRODUCT_TYPE, NAME_SELLER_INDUSTRY, NAME_PAYMENT_TYPE, NAME_YIELD_GROUP. We will work on the following columns to sanitize the information

[ a ] Name Contract Type [ b ] Name Client Type [ c ] Name Portfolio [ d ] Code Reject Reason [ e ] Name Cash Loan Purpose [ f ] Name Goods Category

But before we get going with the coding, I would like to introduce the the concept of Proportion Replacement which we will be using quite a bit in this section. We can replace the inconsistent values in our columns using the proprtion of existing values. If the Gender column as 30% Male and 70% Female and has 100 missing values, we can replace these 100 values with a 30% Male values and 70% female values, so 30 rows will be randomly tagged as Male and 70 rows will be tagged as Female. This way we will be able to treat our missing, null or inconsistent values without changing the underlaying data distribution. For this we have create a function called yCube_Prop_Replace, which we will put in full action in this section.

We will use Pivot table to understand this in bit detail and replace the XNA values based on following logic

If PRODUCT_COMBINATION has entries related to Card Street or Card X-Sell we will change the XNA values in NAME_PORTFOLIO as Cards

If PRODUCT_COMBINATION has entries related to any of the CASH segment we will change the XNA values in NAME_PORTFOLIO as Cash

If PRODUCT_COMBINATION has entries related to any of the POS segment we will change the XNA values in NAME_PORTFOLIO as POS Top

CODE_REJECT_REASON this is another important column we have as it holds details pertaining to loan rejections i.e. reasons for denial of a particular loan. There is a substantial amount of XNA values in this column. We will first draw a pivot to see the count of each values in this column in relation to NAME_CONTRACT_STATUS column, as it will give a clear view of all reject reasons.

  1. It is clear from the pivot that XNA values are the missing values for Refused Contract status is the highest (5234)

  2. There are 8 XNA values for Approved loan type, which is obviously erroneous entry and we will change this to Approved (as reject reasons are not needed for approved loans and this way we would clearly understand while performing analysis later)

  3. There is 1 XAP under Refused loan, which is again an invalid entry and we will change this back to XNA

  4. We will also tag XAP under cancelled category to Client, as a loan can only be cancelled by applicant himself (if it was cancelled by bank it would be tagged at reject) this will help us to clearly understand the code while performing analysis at later stages

After doing all this we have 5234 entries under XNA for reject types without any reject code. We will use proportionate method to fill these XNA values with existing reasons. In a proportionate method, we will calculate the existing proportion of reject reasons in our database, and replace the XNA values with same proportion, so that our overall analysis is not skewed, at the same time we will have complete data columns to work with.

We have created a user defined function to do this trick for us, for this function to work we will first change the XNA values to Null entry and they use this function to automatically replace the values based on existing proportions of each reject reason count. Top

9. Working with Outliers Go Back to Glossary¶

Now we are ready to move into another important section of our data preparation, working with the outliers. By the end of this segment we have already and informally entered into Exploratory Data Analysis segment. Before we get further on this lets understand what are outliers.

An outlier is an observation that lies at an abnormal distance from other values in a random sample from a population. There are well accepted ways to identify the outlier in statistics, one of the most common method is to check the shape of the data using data distribution for certain type of data, other prominent methods includes Box and Whisker plots, which is based on the percentile method of data distribution. In this section we will analyze some of the critical columns to identify the outliers and find a way to work with them.

The reason I have stated certain type of data in the above paragraph is becuase, we can use the percentile distribution method more accurately only on Continuous data and pseudo Continuous data, in case of discrete count data, the above method will not reliably detect outliers because the fitting procedure we use in itself is liable to being pulled towards the outliers, which in statistics is known as masking effect. Again depending on the type of count variable (more importantly on poisson distributed data with given value), detection method may slightly vary. In order to best tackle this, we will use data transformation methods) using squre root and then use identifycation processes base on Median(MED) and Mean Absolute Deviation (MAD) and pack it in our formula yCube_sqRtransform for easier application.

However it is important to note that, understanding outlier is a combination of Art and Science, as a value may appear out of the set from a statistical analysis perspective but if we look at it closely, it may be a valid data point which we cannot ignore. Hence, before we delete a set of values as outliers, it is important to do a thorough study. It is also highly advisable to treat outliers separately rather than deleting them, especially in case if there are too many of them.

We also need to understand outliers from the prespective of other related columns, for example, if we are drawing a random box-plot of income for all our applicant, we will for sure get too many outliers, as data like Salary is heavily dependent on type of Occupation, so in scenario like this we need to use Occupation as a group by and see outliers in each segment of Occupation. This method is generally termed as `Rational Subgrouping` in statistical analysis

9B. Outlier Treatment Go Back to Glossary¶

Few of the outliers are quite straight forward to work while other may need an elaborative preparation and study before removing it. In this segment we will look into some of the methods that we can deploy to tackle the outlier problem.

[ a ] Apply General Logic to work with outliers [ b ] Data Transformation Method [ c ] Understanding percentile distribution and Inter Quartile Ranges ( IQR )

[ d ] Segmenting Outliers based on IQR

Data Transformation and Outlier identification for Count Data¶

For a small set of values, we can use the above General Logic to work with outliers, however it is not possible everytime and we may need more discrete method to establish the outliers. In this section we will look at Data Transformation and MAD and MED ways to identify an outlier, as stated above we will use our function yCube_sqRtransform and identify if each of our count columns above have any outiers. In simple words the functions does the following

Transform the count data using Squreroot Method =2

We will identify Y as an outlier if > med() + 3, the constant (3) in this can be changed as needed

For every column we apply this function, a new column is created which will hold if a specific data point is an outlier or normal

General Logic to work with outliers¶

Lets go back to our CNT_CHILDREN, CNT_PAYMENTS & CNT_FAM_MEMBERS columns and see if we can work on removing the outliers:

CNT_CHILDREN column has values as high as 19, which is obviously an erroneous entry, but somehow this co-relates with the CNT_FAM_MEMBERS column. It may be due to a formulated column, which automaticall calculates Count of Family members based on Children Count etc. We will filter values greater than 6 children, and read through some related columns like Martial Status and Count of Family Members

For Martial status as Single we will change CNT\_CHILDREN value to 0

For Married and Divorced we will change these value to the MODE value of the same column (which is 1 for this CNT\_CHILDREN)

For CNT_FAM_MEMBERS we will impute mode to any value above than 7 family members

For CNT_PAYMENTS we don't have to do any treatment due to the nature of the information this column holds. This column do have some outliers, but a loan can easily upto 80 Payment count which is the maximum in this case. So we will leave the data in this column as is.

We will also remove the maximum value from AMT_REQ_CREDIT_BUREAU as it is unusually high in the data setTop

Inter Quartile Range¶

Not all columns can be treated for outliers with same logic, in this segment we will look at another important method of working with outliers called Inter Quartile Ranges (IQR) >

The IQR is calculated as the difference between the 75th and the 25th percentiles of the data and defines the box in a box and whisker plot.

The IQR can be used to identify outliers by defining limits on the sample values that are a factor kof the IQR below the 25th percentile or above the 75th percentile. The common value for the factor k is the value 1.5 however you can use other factors also depending on various conditions

We can calculate the percentiles of a dataset using the percentile() NumPy function that takes the dataset and specification of the desired percentile. The IQR can then be calculated as the difference between the 75th and 25th percentiles.

We have created two user defined function to help us segment Outliers from our various columns

yCube_iQr_gRp - This function is helful where we need to calculate Inter Quartile Range for a column grouped by another column. This is particularly important when we are dealing with Rational Subgrouping

yCube_iQr - This function is helpful where we don't have to segment IQR based on grouping. For example Days Employed is not dependent on any of the other categorical variable, so we can look at this column as a whole and calculate IQR and then the outliersTop

Segmenting Outliers in our Data Frame¶

In this segment we will segment our data values in each columns, if they are outiler basis the two methods that we have discussed so far.

Outlier Segmentation using Data Transformation Method

Transform the count data using Squreroot Method =2

We will identify Y as an outlier if > med() + 3, the constant (3) in this can be changed as needed

For every column we apply this function, a new column is created which will hold if a specific data point is an outlier or normal

Outlier Segmentation using IQR method

we will look at Q1 and Q3 using python function and calculate the Inter Quartile Range (IQR)

any value less that 1.5 times the IQR from Q1 we will name it as L_Outlier (Lower Outlier)

any value more than 1.5 times the IQR from Q3we will name it as U_Outlier (Upper Outlier)

any value in between the above two ranges, we will name it as Normal (non-outliers)

This will help us to analyze only a segment of data we want to without be deleting any critical information from outer data set. Top

11. Exploratory Data Analytics Go Back to Glossary¶

We have come a long way in terms of cleaning our data, imputing and deleting unnecessary values in both of our Application Data and Previous Application Data data frame and removing outliers to make it more meaningful and quote unquote normal. Now we are ready to move into the most critical and interesting segment of our work, Data Analysis. In this segment we will work on combined sets of df_app and df_pre dataframes called df_cmb and bring out all the interesting and critical information in the dataset with the help of univarate and multivarate data analysis. We will also use several parametric and nonparametric statistical analysis to draw some insights and statistically validated output from our data.

In order for us to understand the outcomes, we will try do segment our analysis basis the type of variables we have in our data set. We will perform our Data Analysis basis following variables types. Remember our main **`VILLAIN`** is alwyas **`Loan Defaults`** which is our target variable and fortunately our column name is also **`TARGET`**

Output Variable -['TARGET'] - this is our target variable, all our focus would be around this column which holds binomial data

Binomial factors - ['NAME_CONTRACT_TYPE', 'CODE_GENDER','NAME_TYPE_SUITE_NEW','FLAG_OWN_CAR', 'FLAG_OWN_REALTY','DEF_CNT_SOCIAL','LIVE_CITY_NOT_WORK_CITY', 'LIVE_REGION_NOT_WORK_REGION', 'REG_CITY_NOT_LIVE_CITY', 'REG_CITY_NOT_WORK_CITY', 'REG_REGION_NOT_LIVE_REGION', 'REG_REGION_NOT_WORK_REGION'] - These columns contains only two probable outputs, Yes or No, True or False, 0 or 1 and Male or Female. This type of data is known as binomial data, and hence they tend to follow a `binomial distribution`. We will have to perform a set of non-parametric tests on these types of data.

Polynomial factors - ['PREV_NAME_CONTRACT_TYPE', 'PREV_NAME_CONTRACT_STATUS', 'PREV_CODE_REJECT_REASON', 'NAME_CLIENT_TYPE', 'NAME_INCOME_TYPE_NEW', 'OCCUPATION_TYPE_NEW', 'NAME_FAMILY_STATUS', 'NAME_EDUCATION_TYPE', 'NAME_HOUSING_TYPE','CHANNEL_TYPE' ,'NAME_PORTFOLIO','CNT_FAM_MEMBERS','AMT_REQ_CREDIT_BUREAU','DAYS_BIRTH', 'DAYS_DECISION', 'DAYS_EMPLOYED', 'DAYS_ID_PUBLISH', 'DAYS_REGISTRATION', 'FLAG_DOCUMENT_COUNT','REGION_RATING_CLIENT', REGION_RATING_CLIENT_W_CITY', 'REGION_RATING_CLIENT', 'REGION_RATING_CLIENT_W_CITY','NAME_GOODS_CATEGORY', 'NAME_CASH_LOAN_PURPOSE'] - these columns have multiple outputs, some even extend to counts we cannot represent in a categorical plot. We need to perform comparaitve graphical represenation for this type of data, especially if the target is a binomial variable. We also have a set of `COUNT DATA` in some of these factors like `'DAYS_ID_PUBLISH'`, some of these count data are of finite nature like `'CNT_FAM_MEMBERS'` which can take a maximum of a certain finite number (single digit in our case), and then we have some other count variables which can take any integer value like `'DAYS_DECISION'`. Depending on type of Polynomial factors we will use various graphical representation. Again for these type of data we will have to do Non Parametric test for statistical inferences.

Continuous factors - ['AMT_INCOME_TOTAL', 'AMT_APPLICATION', 'AMT_CREDIT', 'PREV_AMT_CREDIT', 'AMT_ANNUITY', 'PREV_AMT_ANNUITY','AMT_DOWN_PAYMENT', 'RATE_DOWN_PAYMENT', 'EXT_SOURCE_AVG', 'REGION_POPULATION_RELATIVE','AMT_GOODS_PRICE', 'PREV_AMT_GOODS_PRICE'] - these columns contain what is known as contineous variable. These type of data can take any value in a contineous scale. For these type of data we can perform parametric statistical tests.

Depending on the type of variable we are dealing with, some of our tests, procedure and assumptions will vary. We will talk about them in each section as we encounter them.

Also I am sure you must be wondering where are few of the data columns, why arn't we analyzing them, well its most likely due to the fact that they are dependent factors. For example , CNT_CHILDREN column is direclty dependent on CNT_FAMILY_MEMBERS, including such dependent variables specially in statistical treatment result in something called Confounding, which results in some inaccuracy in the estimated measures.Similarly we have 'AMT_ANNUITY', 'PREV_AMT_ANNUITY' which are direclty dependent on 'AMT_CREDIT'and 'PREV_AMT_CREDIT' (remember annuity is a derived metric based on these factors).

Dependent factors ['AMT_ANNUITY', 'PREV_AMT_ANNUITY', 'CNT_CHILDREN', 'RATE_DOWN_PAYMENT', 'AMT_GOODS_PRICE', 'PREV_AMT_GOODS_PRICE']

Not Required factors - ['SK_ID_CURR', 'SK_ID_PREV','NAME_GOODS_CATEGORY', 'NAME_CASH_LOAN_PURPOSE']- these columns are needed for few form of analysis, but at large we will not work with these columns. While 'SK_ID_CURR', 'SK_ID_PREV' helps us to establish relation among two data set but are not factors, 'NAME_GOODS_CATEGORY', 'NAME_CASH_LOAN_PURPOSE' are associated only for a set of data (for loan realted to Goods and Cash) and contains too many null for us to use them in any statistical treatment.

C. Stastistical Data Analysis and Sample Tests Go Back to Glossary¶

So far we have looked into some of the basic pie and bar charts and percentage values (proportions) to understand which of the factors have higher tendency to contribute more towards a loan default or payment difficulties.

While those univarate analysis helped us to bring forth some of the key observations, but just with them we will not help us to make discrete decission. For exampple, we found that Male gender group has a higher proportion of payment difficulties as compated to Female population, but we don't have a clear view of weather it was merely one time possibility by chance that male had higher percentage or is it the probability of male defaults is always higher (not merely a reandom chance).

In this segment we will use some of the basic stastistical tests to stastistically estimate higher tendency of a particular proportion over other.

Will take the help of Sample Proportion Tests (also called 2-sample z-test to stastically establish if one proportion has higher likelihood of a particular output as compated to other proportion. A Z-test is a type of hypothesis test that will give a way for you to figure out if results from a test are valid and repeatable or it was merely a random occurance.

Here are some of the assumptions we need to satisfy for Sample Tests

  1. Sample size for our test is more than 30 data points
  2. The assumptions for the binomial distribution are satisfied for both populations
  3. Data should be randomly selected and data points should be independent of each other

Here are the steps we will follow for our sample proportion tests

  1. State the null and alternate hypothesis (H0 and Ha)
  2. We will chose al alpha level of 0.05 - Alpha level also known as significance level is the probability of making the wrong decision when the null hypothesis is true. So when we select 0.05, we will have 5% random chance of our test giving us wrong result.
  3. Use python stastistical library to calculate Probability Values as well as Z stastistics and create a simple python function to give us an outcome

Always remember P-Low Null Hypothesis Go

Sample Proportion Tests for Binomial Columns vs. the target¶

We have seen in our Univarate Analysis section that Male have a slightly higher default rate of 11.11% compared to Female gender which stands at 7.9%

We will know test this samples to see was it merely by a chance that our Male proportion was higher, or does it have a higher likelyhood of repeating (Male proptions will be different to Female proportions most of the time)

So as you can see we can, Reject Null Hypothesis The likelyhood of Male Proportions being different than that of the Female Proportion is high.

Note that p value is used in hypothesis testing is to help us support or reject the null hypothesis. The p value is the evidence against a null hypothesis. The smaller the p-value, the stronger the evidence that you should reject the null hypothesis.That is why in the above test our P value is 0.0000 with which we can reject the Null Hypothesis, if P value is greate than the alpha, we would have Failed to reject the null hypothesis

NB: P values are expressed as decimals although it may be easier to understand what they are if you convert them to a percentage. For example, a p value of 0.0254 is 2.54%. This means there is a 2.54% chance your results could be random (i.e. happened by chance). Thats pretty tiny. On the other hand, a large p-value of .9(90%) means your results have a 90% probability of being completely random and not due to anything in your experiment. Therefore, the smaller the p-value, the more important (significant) your result is.

We will carry on with simiar proportion test for rest of our Binomial Columns (Columns with two outcomes) ['NAME_CONTRACT_TYPE','CODE_GENDER','FLAG_OWN_CAR','FLAG_OWN_REALTY','REG_REGION_NOT_LIVE_REGION', 'REG_REGION_NOT_WORK_REGION','LIVE_REGION_NOT_WORK_REGION', 'REG_CITY_NOT_LIVE_CITY', 'REG_CITY_NOT_WORK_CITY', 'NAME_TYPE_SUITE_NEW','LIVE_CITY_NOT_WORK_CITY']

ChiSquare Test for Multinomial Data Columns¶

We have so far worked with two proportions tests that we used in Binomial Data types, and used stastistical methods to establish if any two set of proportions are different in terms of loan defaults. Now we have a couple of very interesting columns, but these columns hold information which when summarized will give more than just 2 factors, in other words they don't satisfy the binomial distribution citeria for Proportion Test. For these columns we will be working on another type of stastistical test known as Chi Square Test

Our Null and Alternative Hypothesis for this tests can be stated as below

Null Hypothesis(H0) - two or more (given set of) categorical variables are independent in some population

Alternate Hypothesis(H1) - two or more (given set of) categorical variables are not independent in some population

Before we continue, let's first make sure we understand what independence really means in the first place.

In short, independence means that one variable doesn't say anything about another variable. A different way of saying the exact same thing is that independence means that the relative frequencies of one variable are identical over all levels of some other variable.

We will perform ChiSquare test of independence for our following Multinomial Columns ['CNT_CHILDREN', 'NAME_EDUCATION_TYPE','NAME_FAMILY_STATUS','REGION_RATING_CLIENT', 'NAME_HOUSING_TYPE', 'REGION_RATING_CLIENT_W_CITY','NAME_INCOME_TYPE_NEW''OCCUPATION_TYPE_NEW', 'FLAG_DOCUMENT_COUNT']

The test result for each column will be summarized at the end.

Our - CNT_CHILDREN column holds information regarding the number of children for each applicant. It holds categorical numeric values like 1,2,3,4 and 5. We are now interested to know if there is a stastistical difference (or Similarity) among these categorical values and Probability to Default. We will be able to analyze this using ChiSquare Test of Independence. The chi-square independence test is a procedure for testing if two or more categorical variables are related in some population.

Much like 2 sample proportion test, ChiSquare Test of Independence will help us to establish if individual proportions of CNT_CHILDREN column values (and other similar categorical columns) are different from each other.

In our graphical section here for our CNT_CHILDREN column we noted that-

The loan default rate is quite consistent (between 8.93% to 10.11%) for customers having children count 0,1,2 an 3, but increases to 14.44% for children count 4 and then decreases to 6.76% for customers having children count 5

What does Children Count say about Loan Default? Well very little to nothing! Why? Because the frequency distributions of Loan Defaults are identical over Children Count. So with the help of ChiSquare test we will be able validate Stastistically if the Loan Default is Independent of Children count

Student's Test and Moods Median tests for Contineous Data Columns¶

So far we have looked into some of the categorical variables only, but we have some important contineous data columns like **Overall Income of Applicants/Customers**. Say if we want to see if Higher income group has lower probability of default or vice versa, or if we want to see if the lower external credit score results in higher defaults, how do we do it?

This is where we can use tests like **Student T Tests**,**Welch's T Test** and **Moods Median Test** depending on few observations and underlying assumptions in data.

Much like other stastistical tests, tests for contineous data need to satisfy one additional assumpation, that is data normality. A norma datal in general is free of Outliers or in common word should behave like the most of other data in that column. If we were asked to analze behaviours of Dogs in an experiment, but if our samples has a Lion do we want to analyze that Lion, well similary in any data set, if a group of data is way different than the rest, we will have to analyze them seprately.

There are various Stastistical methods to establish Data Normality, for our study we will take one simple Normality test Procedure called DAgostino and Pearsons method of normality. If our data is Normal, we will carry on with-

Welch's t-test, or unequal variances t-test, whhich is a two-sample location test which is used to test the hypothesis that two populations have equal means. It is named for its creator, Bernard Lewis Welch, and is an adaptation of Student's t-test, Welch's t-test test is more reliable when the two samples have unequal variances and/or unequal sample sizes. These tests are often referred to as "unpaired" or "independent samples" t-tests, as they are typically applied when the statistical units underlying the two samples being compared are non-overlapping. Its is a parametric test, or in other way our data needs to be normal for us to perform this test.

Our Null and Alternative Hypothesis for this tests can be stated as below

Null Hypothesis(H0) - the average external credit score is same between defaulters and non defaulters

Alternate Hypothesis(H1) - the external credit score income of Defaulters is significantly different than that of Non Defaulters

And if our data is not normal, we will use another non parametric test called

Moods Median Test, this is a nonparametric test that is used to test the equality of medians from two or more populations. Therefore, it provides a nonparametric alternative to the Student's t-test, i.e we can use it withough assuming the underlying normality condition. The Moods median test works when the Y variable is continuous, discrete-ordinal or discrete-count, and the X variable is discrete with two or more attributes.

Our Null and Alternative Hypothesis for this tests can be stated as below

Null Hypothesis(H0) - the median of income is same between defaulters and non defaulters

Alternate Hypothesis(H1) - the median income of Defaulters is significantly different than that of Non Defaulters Top

D. Correlation between input variables and Loan Defaults Go Back to Glossary¶

All of the statistical tests done so far has helped us to establish existance or non-esistance of significant relationship between our input variables (like Gender, Income etc.) and output variable (Loan Defaults), but until now we don't know how much of a relationship exists between the input and the output variables. Now its time to assign a numerical value to our relationship using Correlation Analysis. But before we start drawing random heatmaps, it it critical for us to understand Correlation and different methods available to us in calculating Correlation Coefficient, which is dependend on type of data we have.

Correlation is a bivariate analysis that measures the strength of association between two variables and the direction of the relationship. In terms of the strength of relationship, the value of the correlation coefficient varies between +1 and -1. A value of 1 indicates a perfect degree of association between the two variables. As the correlation coefficient value goes towards 0, the relationship between the two variables will be weaker. The direction of the relationship is indicated by the sign of the coefficient; a + sign indicates a positive relationship and a sign indicates a negative relationship. Usually, in statistics, we measure following types of correlations: Pearson correlation, Kendall rank correlation, Spearman correlation, Cramr's V correlation and the Point-Biserial correlation. I will quickly touch upon the two correlation we will be using:

Point-Biserial correlation - A point-biserial correlation is used to measure the strength and direction of the association that exists between one continuous variable and one dichotomous variable. It is a special case of the Pearsons correlation, which is applied when you have two continuous variables, whereas in this case one of the variables is measured on a dichotomous scale . We will use this method to calculate Correlation for the Loan Defaults which is dichotomous scale of 0 and 1 (for no default and default) and AMT_INCOME_TOTAL and EXT_SOURCE_AVG which are contineous variables

Cramr's V correlation - The Cramrs V (also known as Cramrs ) will help us to measure the strength of association between two nominal variables. Cramrs V is a nonparametric statistic used in cross-tabulated table data. These data are usually measured at the nominal level, although some researchers will use Cramrs V with ordinal data or collapsed (grouped) interval or ration data. This test is useful for us to establish mathematical relation between our Loan Defaults and nominal columns like NAME_CONTRACT_TYPE, CODE_GENDER, FLAG_OWN_CAR, FLAG_OWN_REALTY etc. With this we will no be able to calculate negative correlation as correlation cofficient in this case will range from 0 to +1.

While Point-Biserial Correlation is built on to scipy library, for Cramer Correlation we constructed custom function to calculate the same YCube_Cramer_V

Data Imbalance¶

Imbalanced data typically refers to a classification problem where the number of observations per class is not equally distributed; often you'll have a large amount of data/observations for one class (referred to as the majority class), and much fewer observations for one or more other classes (referred to as the minority class).

Having majority of one value in the dataset may result in what is called Aplah and Beta errors or Type I and Type II errors.

In our data set also we have clear data imbalance problem, and it has been shown repeatedly in our Exploratory Data Analysis segment. For example, we have <10% of defaulters while rest 90% are non defaulters. Well as a bank we always wanted this, but from a modeling prespective, this may cause some errors in our predictions.

While there are many established ways to work out with this, some of which are now embeded as a part of Machine Learning Algorithms (like Oversampling, Undersampling and SMOTE etc), on easy way to deal with these kind of problem is 'Random Sampling', we can randomly sample the minory class and duplicate the sampled observation. In our next segment we will surely look more in terms of sampling other algorithmns to deal with this problem.
